(1372, 'widget_custom_widget', 'a:5:{i:4;a:5:{s:5:\"title\";s:12:\"Brain Tumors\";s:4:\"text\";s:567:\"Brain tumors are tumors which take origin from brain tissue or its outer coverings (membranes), skull bone or malignant (cancerous) tumors which spread to brain from other organs (metastasis). There are many brain tumor types including gliomas, meningiomas, schwannomas, pituitary adenomas, pineal tumors, embryonal tumors, medulloblastomas, PNET, mixed neuro-glial tumors, etc. Of these brain tumors, some tumors are of good character, benign, not malignant while slightly more than half of them are  unfortunately considered ‘brain cancers’ and thus malignant.\";s:4:\"link\";s:13:\"/brain-tumors\";s:11:\"link_target\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"image_uri\";s:70:\"http://localhost/profserdar/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/brain-tumor.png\";}i:5;a:5:{s:5:\"title\";s:12:\"Spine Tumors\";s:4:\"text\";s:458:\"They are 4-5 times less common than brain tumors and are generally more benign. They can occur above the outer membrane of the spinal cord (epidural), as well as under the outer membrane (intradural) and even inside the spinal cord (intramedullary). Astrocytomas, epandymomas, meningiomas and schwannomas are the most common spinal cord tumors. They can occur in any part of the spinal cord, starting from the neck and ending with the back, waist and coccyx.\";s:4:\"link\";s:13:\"/spine-tumors\";s:11:\"link_target\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"image_uri\";s:64:\"http://localhost/profserdar/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/spine.png\";}i:6;a:5:{s:5:\"title\";s:13:\"Lumbar Hernia\";s:4:\"text\";s:747:\"All over the world, 80% of people complain of severe low back pain at least once in their lifetime, and the most important reason for this is herniated disc. Loss of labor and treatment costs due to herniated disc are over $100 million annually in the United States. The disc material, which is located between the lumbar spine and allows the bone surfaces to attach to each other, deteriorates over time, and the gel-like structure (nucleus pulposus) in the inner part hardens, ruptures the outer membrane and herniates, thus creating pressure on the nerve roots that go to the outer membrane of the spinal cord and the leg. Pain, numbness and loss of strength radiating from the waist down to the hips, legs, feet and toes are common complaints.\";s:4:\"link\";s:14:\"/lumbar-hernia\";s:11:\"link_target\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"image_uri\";s:63:\"http://localhost/profserdar/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/back.png\";}i:7;a:5:{s:5:\"title\";s:11:\"Neck Hernia\";s:4:\"text\";s:258:\"Neck hernias are seen at younger ages ( 30-40 years ) than waist hernias. In neck hernias, which are more common in active ages and in office workers, pain radiating to the neck and arm can seriously reduce the quality of life and prevent daily routine work.\";s:4:\"link\";s:12:\"/neck-hernia\";s:11:\"link_target\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"image_uri\";s:63:\"http://localhost/profserdar/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/neck.png\";}s:12:\"_multiwidget\";i:1;}', 'yes'),
